goals.question: How does the weather condition vary with respect to time?

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data
data = pd.read_csv('weather.csv')

# Plot histogram of temperature
sns.histplot(data=data, x='temperature', kde=True, color='blue')
plt.axvline(data['temperature'].mean(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label='Mean')
plt.axvline(data['temperature'].median(), color='green', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label='Median')
plt.title('What is the distribution of temperature in the dataset?', wrap=True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()
```

```
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data
data = pd.read_csv('weather.csv')

# Convert date field to datetime type
data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], format='%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S', errors='coerce')

# Drop rows with NaT values
data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]

# Line chart of humidity over time
sns.lineplot(x='date', y='humidity', data=data)

# Set chart title
plt.title('How does the humidity vary with respect to time?', wrap=True)

# Rotate x-axis labels for legibility
plt.xticks(rotation=45)

# Show plot
plt.show()
```

```
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data
data = pd.read_csv('weather.csv')

# Convert date field to datetime type
data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], format='%Y-%m-%d', errors='coerce')

# Drop rows with NaT values
data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]

# Create a bar chart of weather condition over time
sns.set_style("whitegrid")
sns.barplot(x="date", y="weather_condition", data=data, palette="Blues_d")

# Set chart title
plt.title("How does the weather condition vary with respect to time?", wrap=True)

# Rotate x-axis labels for legibility
plt.xticks(rotation=45)

# Show plot
plt.show()
